Regulations

Regulations video

Quatuor is a fast-paced strategy game in which two players take turns laying down their pieces and trying to align 4 of them vertically, horizontally or on the main diagonals.

The game is played on a 4x4 board.

Each player has 8 tokens, which he keeps outside the board.

In turn, each player places his piece on the periphery of the board (on the letters "Quatuor").

Pawns cannot be deposited directly at the center.

You don't have to fill all the squares around the perimeter to start pushing pawns.

If there is already a token on the square in question, the player can push it along the row(A), column(B) or large diagonals(C), in the same axis as his pawn arriving from the outside.

There are only two large diagonals, and they are made up of 4 squares like rows or columns.

You can push your pawn or your opponent's pawn.

When a token is pushed, it also pushes the other tokens in the same row, column or on the large diagonal.

However, it is not possible to remove a pawn from the game.

If the line is full, no pawn can be added there.

Note that you can't "jump" an empty square to push a pawn.

In the following example, the white player cannot place his pawn on the letter "O" and push the tokens already in place.

The first player to line up 4 of his pawns along a column, long diagonal or row wins.

If the board is full and no-one has lined up 4 tokens, then it's a draw or you opt for the tie-breaking rule.

If both players simultaneously find themselves with 4 pawns lined up, the game continues.

Tie-breaking rule

(optional)

Once the board is full and you have no more tokens to play with, you must move a row/column/diagonal by removing one of your tokens from the board and placing it back on the vacant square.

You cannot move a line that would cause an opponent's token to fall.

In this example, the white player moves the bottom line to remove a chip of his color and return it to the beginning. This gives him victory on the large diagonal.

If your move also aligns your opponent's chips, the game continues until there is only one winner.

By Louis-David Raymond
